      <!-- When You DON'T Need MOJ -->
      <h2 id="dont-need-moj">When You DON'T Need MOJ Certification</h2>

      <p>
        Here are the common situations where certified translation (without MOJ) is sufficient:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Employment contracts for private companies:</strong> Your employer's HR department typically accepts <a href="/blog/authenticated-translation-moj-vs-certified/">certified translation</a> of your academic documents.</li>
        <li><strong>Bank account opening:</strong> Most UAE banks accept certified translation of supporting documents. Some banks are stricter — always confirm first.</li>
        <li><strong>Free zone company formation:</strong> JAFZA, DMCC, Dubai Internet City, and most other free zones accept English documents. Arabic translation is rarely required for internal processes.</li>
        <li><strong>DIFC and ADGM filings:</strong> Both operate in English. No Arabic translation needed unless you are enforcing across jurisdictions.</li>
        <li><strong>Insurance claims:</strong> Certified translation is generally accepted for medical reports and supporting documents.</li>
        <li><strong>School enrollment:</strong> KHDA-regulated schools in Dubai typically accept certified translation of academic records.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        <a href="/resources/moj-vs-certified/">Our detailed MOJ vs Certified comparison</a> covers the technical differences between the two types.
      </p>

      <!-- When You MUST Have MOJ -->
      <h2 id="must-have-moj">When MOJ Certification Is Mandatory</h2>

      <p>
        No shortcuts here. These submissions require MOJ-certified Arabic translation:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Any court filing</strong> — Dubai Courts, Abu Dhabi Courts, Federal Courts, Sharjah Courts</li>
        <li><strong>Visa and residency applications</strong> — GDRFA, ICP</li>
        <li><strong>Work permit applications</strong> — MOHRE, Tasheel</li>
        <li><strong>Document attestation</strong> — MOFA attestation chain</li>
        <li><strong>Degree equivalency</strong> — <a href="/resources/mohesr-equivalency/">MOHESR Certificate of Recognition</a></li>
        <li><strong>Property transactions</strong> — DLD (Dubai Land Department), DMT (Abu Dhabi)</li>
        <li><strong>Wills and estate matters</strong> — <a href="/legal/wills/">ADJD will registration</a>, probate proceedings</li>
        <li><strong>Criminal matters</strong> — All criminal proceedings in the UAE</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        The legal basis: Federal Decree-Law No. 22 of 2022 regulates the translation profession. Only MOJ-registered translators may practice, and courts may reject translations from unregistered translators. Federal Decree-Law No. 42 of 2022, Article 48 requires certified Arabic translation for all foreign-language documents submitted as evidence.
      </p>

      <!-- The ADJD Exception -->
      <h2 id="adjd-exception">The Abu Dhabi Exception: ADJD Circular No. 8</h2>

      <p>
        Abu Dhabi Judicial Department issued Circular No. 8 of 2023, which exempts certain documents from translation:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Bank statements with primarily numerical content</li>
        <li>Invoices where the key information (amounts, dates, parties) is clear from context</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        This exemption applies only to ADJD proceedings in Abu Dhabi. Dubai Courts, Sharjah Courts, and Federal Courts still require full translation of all documents, including bank statements. Do not assume this exemption applies outside Abu Dhabi.
      </p>

      <!-- Decision Flowchart -->
      <h2 id="quick-check">Quick Decision Check</h2>

      <p>
        Answer these three questions to determine your translation type:
      </p>

      <div class="decision-steps">
        <div class="decision-step">
          <div class="step-number">1</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Where are you submitting?</h3>
            <p><strong>Court, GDRFA, MOHRE, MOFA, MOHESR, DLD?</strong> You need MOJ-certified Arabic translation. No exceptions.</p>
            <p><strong>DIFC, ADGM, bank, private company, free zone?</strong> Continue to question 2.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-step">
